- How would you implement robust path reconstruction for the teleport usages?

## Why This Is Asked
This problem tests dynamic programming on partitioning with a non-linear cost function (distinct character count). It's concrete, implementable, and scales well to typical interview constraints.

## Key Concepts
- DP over prefixes and partition count
- Precomputing distinct character counts for all substrings (O(n²) with two pointers)
- Reconstruction via parent pointers
- Time/space trade-offs

## Code Example
```javascript
function maxPartitionDistinct(s, k) {
  const n = s.length;
  const dist = Array.from({ length: n }, () => Array(n).fill(0));

  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    const seen = new Set();
    for (let j = i; j < n; j++) {
      seen.add(s[j]);
      dist[i][j] = seen.size;
    }
  }

  const dp = Array.from({ length: n + 1 }, () => Array(k + 1).fill(-Infinity));
  const prev = Array.from({ length: n + 1 }, () => Array(k + 1).fill(-1));
  dp[0][0] = 0;

  for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
    for (let t = 1; t <= Math.min(i, k); t++) {
      for (let j = t - 1; j < i; j++) {
        const val = dp[j][t - 1] + dist[j][i - 1];
        if (val > dp[i][t]) {
          dp[i][t] = val;
          prev[i][t] = j;
        }
      }
    }
  }

  const partitions = [];
  let [i, t] = [n, k];
  while (t > 0) {
    const j = prev[i][t];
    partitions.unshift([j, i - 1]);
    i = j;
    t--;
  }

  return { value: dp[n][k], partitions };
}
```

## Why This Is Asked
Tests DP with partitioning and a nontrivial per-substring cost, plus backtracking to recover partitions.

## Key Concepts
- DP over partitions: dp[i][t]
- Precompute cost[l][r] in O(n^2) via two-pointer mismatches
- Backpointers for reconstruction
- Complexity: O(n^2 k) time, O(n^2) space

## Code Example
```javascript
function minCostPalindromePartitions(s, k) {
  const n = s.length;
  const cost = Array.from({length: n}, ()=> Array(n).fill(0));
  for (let l = 0; l < n; l++) {
    for (let r = l; r < n; r++) {
      let a = l, b = r, c = 0;
      while (a < b) { if (s[a] !== s[b]) c++; a++; b--; }
      cost[l][r] = c;
    }
  }
  const dp = Array.from({length: n}, () => Array(k + 1).fill(Infinity));
  const parent = Array.from({length: n}, () => Array(k + 1).fill(-1));
  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) dp[i][1] = cost[0][i];
  for (let t = 2; t <= k; t++) {
    for (let i = t - 1; i < n; i++) {
      for (let p = t - 2; p < i; p++) {
        const val = dp[p][t - 1] + cost[p + 1][i];
        if (val < dp[i][t]) { dp[i][t] = val; parent[i][t] = p; }
      }
    }
  }
  const splits = [];
  let i = n - 1, t = k;
  while (t >= 1) {
    splits.push(i);
    i = parent[i][t];
    t--;
  }
  splits.reverse();
  return { minCost: dp[n - 1][k], partitions: splits };
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you optimize space for large n or small k?
- How would this adapt if cost used a different per-substring metric?

## Why This Is Asked

Tests the ability to design a DP with two choices per step (1- or 2-length blocks), plus reconstruction and complexity awareness.

## Key Concepts

- DP with two dimensions (i, t)
- Transitions for 1-length and 2-length blocks
- Reconstruction via parent pointers
- Time/space trade-offs and potential optimization

## Code Example

```javascript
function maxValueBlocks(A, k){
  const n = A.length;
  const NEG = -1e15;
  const dp = Array.from({length: n+1}, ()=> Array(k+1).fill(NEG));
  const take = Array.from({length: n+1}, ()=> Array(k+1).fill(0));
  dp[0][0] = 0;
  for(let i=1;i<=n;i++){
    for(let t=1;t<=k;t++){
      // 1-length block ending at i-1
      if(dp[i-1][t-1] !== NEG){
        const val = dp[i-1][t-1] + A[i-1];
        if(val > dp[i][t]){ dp[i][t] = val; take[i][t] = 1; }
      }
      // 2-length block ending at i-1
      if(i>=2 && dp[i-2][t-1] !== NEG){
        const val = dp[i-2][t-1] + A[i-2] + A[i-1];
        if(val > dp[i][t]){ dp[i][t] = val; take[i][t] = 2; }
      }
    }
  }
  // reconstruction would trace back from (n, k)
  return dp[n][k];
}
```

