## Why This Is Asked

This question tests dynamic programming over non-overlapping subarrays where block value depends on internal structure, requiring precomputation and reconstruction techniques.

## Key Concepts

- Non-overlapping k blocks in increasing order
- Precomputation of per-block value (peaks inside)
- DP with inner maximization over l
- Reconstruction pointers; time/space trade-offs

## Code Example

```javascript
function maxValueSubarrays(A, k, F, P) {
  const n = A.length;
  const pref = new Array(n+1).fill(0);
  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) pref[i+1] = pref[i] + A[i];
  const peaks = Array.from({length: n}, () => Array(n).fill(0));

  // Precompute peaks
  for (let i = 1; i < n-1; i++) {
    if (A[i-1] < A[i] && A[i] > A[i+1]) {
      for (let l = 0; l <= i; l++) {
        for (let r = i; r < n; r++) {
          peaks[l][r]++;
        }
      }
    }
  }

  const val = (l, r) => pref[r+1] - pref[l] - F - P * peaks[l][r];

  const dp = Array.from({length: n+1}, () => Array(k+1).fill(-Infinity));
  const parent = Array.from({length: n+1}, () => Array(k+1).fill(-1));

  dp[0][0] = 0;

  for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
    for (let t = 1; t <= k; t++) {
      dp[i][t] = dp[i-1][t];
      for (let l = 1; l <= i; l++) {
        if (dp[l-1][t-1] + val(l-1, i-1) > dp[i][t]) {
          dp[i][t] = dp[l-1][t-1] + val(l-1, i-1);
          parent[i][t] = l-1;
        }
      }
    }
  }

  // Reconstruct
  const blocks = [];
  let cur = n, curT = k;
  while (curT > 0 && parent[cur][curT] !== -1) {
    const start = parent[cur][curT];
    blocks.unshift([start, cur-1]);
    cur = start;
    curT--;
  }

  return { max: dp[n][k], blocks };
}
```

## Complexity

- Time: O(n²k) due to nested loops for peaks, DP, and reconstruction
- Space: O(nk) for DP table and parent pointers, reducible to O(n) with rolling arrays

